  "source": "Pediatrics_Nelson_textbook_data.txt - Otitis media with effusion (OME) refers to the presence of fluid in the middle ear without signs or symptoms of acute infection. While most commonly affecting children, this condition can also occur in adults, particularly following upper respiratory tract infections, allergic rhinitis, or barotrauma. The pathophysiology primarily involves eustachian tube dysfunction leading to negative middle ear pressure and subsequent accumulation of sterile fluid. In adults, predisposing factors include upper respiratory infections, allergic rhinitis, sinusitis, nasopharyngeal masses (rare, but requiring evaluation, especially with unilateral persistent effusion), and barotrauma from air travel or diving. Clinical presentation typically includes hearing loss (usually mild to moderate conductive), aural fullness, and occasionally tinnitus. Unlike acute otitis media, pain and fever are notably absent. Otoscopic examination reveals a retracted, opaque tympanic membrane with decreased mobility, often with visible air-fluid levels or bubbles. The light reflex may be absent or distorted. Diagnostic confirmation is obtained through tympanometry, which typically shows a flat (type B) curve indicating reduced compliance of the tympanic membrane. Audiometry demonstrates a conductive hearing loss with preserved bone conduction thresholds. Weber testing lateralizes to the affected ear, and Rinne testing shows bone conduction greater than air conduction on the affected side. Management in adults follows similar principles as in children, though with some differences in emphasis. Observation for 3 months is appropriate for uncomplicated cases, as many resolve spontaneously, particularly those following upper respiratory infections. Treatment of underlying conditions such as allergic rhinitis or sinusitis may expedite resolution. Autoinsufflation techniques (Valsalva maneuver, Politzer device) can temporarily relieve symptoms by equalizing middle ear pressure. Medical interventions including systemic decongestants, antihistamines, and intranasal steroids may be beneficial in cases associated with allergic rhinitis but lack consistent evidence for primary treatment of OME itself. Surgical intervention with tympanostomy tube placement is considered for persistent effusions (>3 months) with significant hearing loss or quality of life impact. In adults, unilateral persistent effusion requires thorough evaluation to rule out nasopharyngeal masses, particularly in high-risk populations. With appropriate management, the prognosis is generally favorable, though recurrence may occur, particularly in patients with persistent eustachian tube dysfunction or allergic disease.",
  "category": "Otolaryngology (ENT – Ear, Nose, and Throat)"
